entries.TEXT:
MP#750 - Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe
Background/Goal: The MLP has demonstrated the ability to resolve the mode structure of a 110 kHz Quasi-Coherent Mode (QCM), directly recording time series snapshots (1.1 MHz sampling rate) of density, electron temperature and plasma potential in the mode layer on multiple electrodes. These measurements have allowed the relative phase angles among these quantities to be resolved and the phase propagation velocity in the plasma frame to be deduced by simultaneously recording the electric field in the mode layer (i.e., accounting for ExB plasma motion). The goal of this MP is to perform similar measurements of the WCM.
Plan: We will work on steps A, B, C, D of the MP.
Diagnostics: - Horizontal probe (ASP) with Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) system connected. The standard Langmuir-Mach probe head must be installed on the A-port drive system. This is the most robust head for high heat flux. - Reflectometer - GPI fast-diode system (may need to change outer gap to accommodate this diagnostic at the risk of altering the 'magic' of the plasma shape in obtaining these low power WCM conditions - need to assess during run time.) - GP-CXRS -- look into sending some fibers into GPI diodes to try to localize the mode with respect to CXRS views - Phase contrast imaging - Fast Mirnov coils - Edge Thomson scattering - FRCECE
Gas Setup: NINJA C-port: 10 PSI He for GPI NINJA F-port: 7 PSI He
ICRF: Yes. Prepare for about 1 MW, D+E DNB: no LH: Yes, if possible Cryopump: No Overnight ECDC: standard parameters
Reload 1140714031. This was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, NL04 ~ 0.5E20, JFT-2M-shaped discharge with 1 MW RF (J-ant) and a very nice WCM. This plasma disrupted at 1.4 seconds, however, so it may need some attention.
Step A - Establish 0.8 MA I-mode 5.4 tesla, 0.8 MA, NL04 ~ 0.6 x1020m-2 discharge but with RF power ramp from 0.5 to 1.0 MW from 0.7 to 1.0 seconds and holding at 1.0 MW until 1.3 seconds. Track onset time of I-mode and WCM and reduce max RF power if possible while maintaining I-mode and WCM.
Step B - Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
Step C - Establish 1.0 MA I-mode If probe survives Step B or if 0.8 MA I-modes/WCMs are found to be poor, increase current to 1.0 MA and optimize/reduce RF power to attain I-mode with good WCM
Step D - Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
If time allows, we will investigate the effect of applying LH power to these low power I-Modes, looking for changes in WCM behavior (MP748), e.g., frequency ramp-down effect as seen for the QCM with LH power.
We will also apply power to the Shoelace antenna at a fixed frequency in the range of the WCM to see if we can drive a drift-like mode in the boundary plasma.

The plot below shows the RMS amplitude between 200 and 500 kHz, averaged across BP1,2, and 3T_ABK (the "top" set) and BP4,5,6T_ABK (the "bottom" set). These coils are situated under tiles on the AB limiter, and survey the same toroidal angles. The top coils are at R=0.9045 m, z=+0.1030 m; the bottom, R=0.9045 m, z=-0.1030 m. The RMS amplitudes are scaled by e^{|ktheta*\Delta r|}, where ktheta=n*B_phi/(R*B_poloidal) is found after making the field-aligned assumption, q=m/n, and taking the straight cylinder approximation for q, and the scrape-off layer is assumed to be quasi-vacuum. They are also scaled by sqrt(2) to return the equivalent sinusoidal amplitude. Also, the signals have been calibrated referenced to the vacuum field of a dipole at R=0.8 m, z=0 m, scanning over frequencies from ~20 kHz to ~1.1 MHz. During the ELM-ing phase there is as much as a factor of two difference between the upper and lower coils, with the upper coils having the larger amplitude. The correction factor applied to the RMS amplitudes for the top and bottom coil sets is shown below - the bottom set is scaled by roughly 7.5, while the top, by 6.5. The minimum distance between the LCFS and the coils used in the scale factor calculation is shown below, and is roughly 2.6 cm for the top coils, and 3.0 cm for the bottom coils.

The plot below shows the RMS amplitude between 200 and 500 kHz, averaged across BP1,2, and 3T_ABK (the "top" set) and BP4,5,6T_ABK (the "bottom" set). These coils are situated under tiles on the AB limiter, and survey the same toroidal angles. The top coils are at R=0.9045 m, z=+0.1030 m; the bottom, R=0.9045 m, z=-0.1030 m. The RMS amplitudes are scaled by e^{|ktheta*\Delta r|}, where ktheta=n*B_phi/(R*B_poloidal) is found after making the field-aligned assumption, q=m/n, and taking the straight cylinder approximation for q, and the scrape-off layer is assumed to be quasi-vacuum. They are also scaled by sqrt(2) to return the equivalent sinusoidal amplitude. In this analysis, in is assumed to be 10 (see other Logbook entries for this shot). Also, the signals have been calibrated referenced to the vacuum field of a dipole at R=0.8 m, z=0 m, scanning over frequencies from ~20 kHz to ~1.1 MHz. During the ELM-ing phase there is as much as a factor of two difference between the upper and lower coils, with the upper coils having the larger amplitude. The correction factor applied to the RMS amplitudes for the top and bottom coil sets is shown below - the bottom set is scaled by roughly 7.5, while the top, by 6.5. The minimum distance between the LCFS and the coils used in the scale factor calculation is shown below, and is roughly 2.6 cm for the top coils, and 3.0 cm for the bottom coils. Broadening the frequency range over which the RMS amplitude is calculated to 100-500 kHz includes more of the activity in the pre-ELM-ing phase. There is also a larger relative amplitude on the upper coils in this earlier phase, but it is less-pronounced than that during the ELM-ing phase - a factor of 1.3 vs. 2.0. It's hard to say how accurate this method is at resolving poloidal asymmetries, though a factor of 2 should be within its resolution.

Toroidal mode number analysis, per request of Seung Gyou Baek. Analysis using Mirnov Coils BP4,5,6T_ABK (Mirnov coils under tiles on lower portion of AB split limiter). It looks like the rough approximation of the toroidal mode number of the fluctuations given by this coil set is n~+10, but there may be simultaneous activity at several different mode numbers - turbulence rather than a single mode? If there is a transition in mode number between early activity in the ELM-free phase and later activity, it is subtle, with n dropping from perhaps 10 to 9. During the ELM-ing phase, there may be transitions in mode number, as shown by the zoomed-in section below. A different Mirnov coil set, BP123T_ABK (under tiles on the upper portion of the AB split limiter), gives roughly the same toroidal mode number before the ELM-ing phase, but the mode number after ELMs begin is shifted down to around n=+7,8 instead of 8,9. This is despite a calibration that should align the phases of the coils fairly accurately. I wouldn't speculate on up-down asymmetry from this, alone, however. It is a fairly small difference.

These coils are situated under tiles on the AB limiter, and survey the same toroidal angles. The top coils are at R=0.9045 m, z=+0.1030 m; the bottom, R=0.9045 m, z=-0.1030 m. The RMS amplitudes are scaled by e^{|ktheta*\Delta r|}, where ktheta=n*B_phi/(R*B_poloidal) is found after making the field-aligned assumption, q=m/n, and taking the straight cylinder approximation for q, and the scrape-off layer is assumed to be quasi-vacuum. They are also scaled by sqrt(2) to return the equivalent sinusoidal amplitude. Also, the signals have been calibrated referenced to the vacuum field of a dipole at R=0.8 m, z=0 m, scanning over frequencies from ~20 kHz to ~1.1 MHz. During the ELM-ing phase there is as much as a factor of two difference between the upper and lower coils, with the upper coils having the larger amplitude. The correction factor applied to the RMS amplitudes for the top and bottom coil sets is shown below - the bottom set is scaled by roughly 7.5, while the top, by 6.5.

MP#750 - Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe
Background/Goal: The MLP has demonstrated the ability to resolve the mode structure of a 110 kHz Quasi-Coherent Mode (QCM), directly recording time series snapshots (1.1 MHz sampling rate) of density, electron temperature and plasma potential in the mode layer on multiple electrodes. These measurements have allowed the relative phase angles among these quantities to be resolved and the phase propagation velocity in the plasma frame to be deduced by simultaneously recording the electric field in the mode layer (i.e., accounting for ExB plasma motion). The goal of this MP is to perform similar measurements of the WCM.
Plan: We will work on steps A, B, C, D of the MP.
Diagnostics: - Horizontal probe (ASP) with Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) system connected. The standard Langmuir-Mach probe head must be installed on the A-port drive system. This is the most robust head for high heat flux. - Reflectometer
- GPI fast-diode system (may need to change outer gap to accommodate this diagnostic at the risk of altering the â??magicâ?? of the plasma shape in obtaining these low power WCM conditions - need to assess during run time.) - GP-CXRS -- look into sending some fibers into GPI diodes to try to localize the mode with respect to CXRS views - Phase contrast imaging - Fast Mirnov coils - Edge Thomson scattering - FRCECE
Gas Setup: NINJA C-port: 10 PSI He for GPI NINJA F-port: 7 PSI He
ICRF: Yes. Prepare for about 1 MW, D+E DNB: no LH: Yes, if possible Cryopump: No Overnight ECDC: standard parameters
Reload 1140714031. This was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, NL04 ~ 0.5E20, JFT-2M-shaped discharge with 1 MW RF (J-ant) and a very nice WCM. This plasma disrupted at 1.4 seconds, however, so it may need some attention.
Step A â?? Establish 0.8 MA I-mode 5.4 tesla, 0.8 MA, NL04 ~ 0.6 x1020m-2 discharge but with RF power ramp from 0.5 to 1.0 MW from 0.7 to 1.0 seconds and holding at 1.0 MW until 1.3 seconds. Track onset time of I-mode and WCM and reduce max RF power if possible while maintaining I-mode and WCM.
Step B â?? Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
Step C â?? Establish 1.0 MA I-mode If probe survives Step B or if 0.8 MA I-modes/WCMs are found to be poor, increase current to 1.0 MA and optimize/reduce RF power to attain I-mode with good WCM
Step D â?? Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
If time allows, we will investigate the effect of applying LH power to these low power I-Modes, looking for changes in WCM behavior (MP748), e.g., frequency ramp-down effect as seen for the QCM with LH power.
We will also apply power to the Shoelace antenna at a fixed frequency in the range of the WCM to see if we can drive a drift-like mode in the boundary plasma.

MP748 - "Looking for Poloidal Asymmetry in Weakly Coherent Mode" - Piggyback
This MP will piggyback on the run for MP750 "Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe," since both require I-modes with minimal ICRF power.
The principal goal of the run will be to get a full scan of the edge with the MLP while maintaining a small enough outer gap to observe the WCM on the Mirnov coil poloidal arrays. This will provide a simultaneous dataset of WCM poloidal asymmetry (if it is observed) combined with reliable edge profiles (particularly, potential). PCI and other fluctuation diagnostics will also provide essential data.

MP748 - "Looking for Poloidal Asymmetry in Weakly Coherent Mode" - Piggyback
This MP will piggyback on the run for MP750 "Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe," since both require I-modes with minimal ICRF power.
The principal goal of the run will be to get a full scan of the edge with the MLP while maintaining a small enough outer gap to observe the WCM on the Mirnov coil poloidal arrays. This will provide a simultaneous dataset of WCM poloidal asymmetry (if it is observed) combined with reliable edge profiles (particularly, potential). PCI and other fluctuation diagnostics will also provide essential data.
If time allows and it will not interfere with satisfying the requirements for accomplishing MP750, we will scan the centroid upward and downward via swinging ZCUR by 2 cm. MP#750 - Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe
Background/Goal: The MLP has demonstrated the ability to resolve the mode structure of a 110 kHz Quasi-Coherent Mode (QCM), directly recording time series snapshots (1.1 MHz sampling rate) of density, electron temperature and plasma potential in the mode layer on multiple electrodes. These measurements have allowed the relative phase angles among these quantities to be resolved and the phase propagation velocity in the plasma frame to be deduced by simultaneously recording the electric field in the mode layer (i.e., accounting for ExB plasma motion). The goal of this MP is to perform similar measurements of the WCM.
Plan: We will work on steps A, B, C, D of the MP.
Diagnostics: - Horizontal probe (ASP) with Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) system connected. The standard Langmuir-Mach probe head must be installed on the A-port drive system. This is the most robust head for high heat flux. - Reflectometer
- GPI fast-diode system (may need to change outer gap to accommodate this diagnostic at the risk of altering the 'magic' of the plasma shape in obtaining these low power WCM conditions - need to assess during run time.) - GP-CXRS -- look into sending some fibers into GPI diodes to try to localize the mode with respect to CXRS views - Phase contrast imaging - Fast Mirnov coils - Edge Thomson scattering - FRCECE
Gas Setup: NINJA C-port: 10 PSI He for GPI NINJA F-port: 7 PSI He
ICRF: Yes. Prepare for about 1 MW, D+E DNB: no LH: Yes, if possible Cryopump: No Overnight ECDC: standard parameters
Reload 1140714031. This was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, NL04 ~ 0.5E20, JFT-2M-shaped discharge with 1 MW RF (J-ant) and a very nice WCM. This plasma disrupted at 1.4 seconds, however, so it may need some attention.
Step A - Establish 0.8 MA I-mode 5.4 tesla, 0.8 MA, NL04 ~ 0.6 x1020m-2 discharge but with RF power ramp from 0.5 to 1.0 MW from 0.7 to 1.0 seconds and holding at 1.0 MW until 1.3 seconds. Track onset time of I-mode and WCM and reduce max RF power if possible while maintaining I-mode and WCM.
Step B - Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
Step C - Establish 1.0 MA I-mode If probe survives Step B or if 0.8 MA I-modes/WCMs are found to be poor, increase current to 1.0 MA and optimize/reduce RF power to attain I-mode with good WCM
Step D - Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.
If time allows, we will investigate the effect of applying LH power to these low power I-Modes, looking for changes in WCM behavior (MP748), e.g., frequency ramp-down effect as seen for the QCM with LH power.
We will also apply power to the Shoelace antenna at a fixed frequency in the range of the WCM to see if we can drive a drift-like mode in the boundary plasma.

The basic equilibrium run today was the so-called JFT-2M shape, an LSN configuration with high lower triangularity. All shots were at 800 kA, 5.4 T and mid 10^19 m^-2 density.
The starting shot was 1140714031, and throughout the run only relatively minor tuning of gaps, RXL and ZXU was done.
An important point prior to the run was made by Steve Wolfe, who suggested reducing the slew rate of the EF1 power supply during the first 0.6 s in order to avoid a potential crowbar. The fix was implemented on ZXU on the first shot by delay the point at (0.45sec, +.08 meters) in 1140714031 to (0.60sec, +.08meters). This programming was maintained during the run. Thus, in the future, loading any of the shots from today should not run into the EF1 crowbar problem.
Scorecard: 31 attempts at plasma, 1 dud (fill pressure too low), 3 disruptions during flattop (separatrix grazing top knee in inner wall divertor?), 3 disruptions in rampdown and 24 full length, typically ramping down to 100 kA.

MP748 - "Looking for Poloidal Asymmetry in Weakly Coherent Mode" - Piggyback
Summary: Our reference equilibrium, 1140714031, was a low-power I-mode with a long-lived WCM. We attempted to reproduce this discharge today. However, while we did see a transition in the fluctuation spectrum and a "mode" around 300 kHz, or perhaps dithering between 200 and 300 kHz, we didn't get quite the same WCM as before. Instead, both the MLP and Mirnov coil spectra seemed to be dominated by intermittent ELM-like events. Density was not well-controlled, either, and swings in density seemed to have an effect on the WCM-like feature in the spectrum.
Shots 1150722027-31 were specialized for MP748
1120722027 - 1.0-1.4 s ICRF, 800 kW fixed; small gap; LH from 1.2-1.4 - no WCM, but quasi-H-mode 1120722028 - 1.0-1.4 s ICRF, 600-800 kW ramp; small gap; LH from 1.2-1.4 - still no WCM, but rather quasi-H-mode 1150722029 - Recall 1150722018, but try for higher LH power - got a few short blips of LH; dithering WCM apparent 1150722030 - Upward ZCUR scan (-3 cm to -1 cm) - dithering 300-200 kHz WCM apparent, with dropping center frequency; still not much LH 1150722031 - Downward ZCUR (-1 cm to -3 cm) - lower-frequency WCM-like feature - nice LH power ramp, getting near 700 kW before tripping and giving short pulses; LH seems to affect spectrum strongly, repairing WCM <-this is probably the most interesting shot from this set
Also, ran the Shoelace antenna in transmitter mode for Shots 20 to 26, getting around 127 A at around 209.7 kHz on rampdown of Shot 1150722026. In general, it didn't work well when ICRF was running. Interestingly, ICRF power seems to cause the VCO frequency to move around a lot, suggesting some voltage offset appearing on the VCO board. Maybe an RF noise/power supply issue.

The basic equilibrium run today was the so-called JFT-2M shape, an LSN configuration with high lower triangularity. All shots were at 800 kA, 5.4 T and mid 10^19 m^-2 density.
The starting shot was 1140714031, and throughout the run only relatively minor tuning of gaps, RXL and ZXU was done.
An important point prior to the run was made by Steve Wolfe, who suggested reducing the slew rate of the EF1 power supply during the first 0.6 s in order to avoid a potential crowbar. The fix was implemented on ZXU on the first shot by delay the point at (0.45sec, +.08 meters) in 1140714031 to (0.60sec, +.08meters). This programming was maintained during the run. Thus, in the future, loading any of the shots from today should not run into the EF1 crowbar problem.
Scorecard: 31 attempts at plasma, 1 dud (fill pressure too low), 3 disruptions during flattop (separatrix grazing top knee in inner wall divertor?), 2 disruptions in rampdown and 25 full length, typically ramping down to 100 kA.

Session Leader Run Summary
MP#750 â?? "Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe"
Primary Goal: Establish a discharge with a weakly coherent mode (WCM) under low power conditions (~ 1 MW ICRF) using "JFT-2M" plasma shaping; use the A-port scanning Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) diagnostic to interrogate its mode structure in detail -- if the mode exists sufficiently close to the last closed flux surface that the probe can reach it.
MP#748 - "Looking for Poloidal Asymmetry in Weakly Coherent Mode" - Piggyback
Primary Goal: Establish a discharge with a WCM under low power conditions and scan the plasma current centroid upward and downward by 2 cm to look for up-down asymmetries in the mode structure via fast Mirnov coils.
Secondary Goal: Explore the response of the WCM and overall discharge behavior to LHRF applied at the ~0.6 MW level for ~0.1 s pulses.
Result: This was a productive but demanding run to tease out the desired data. We reloaded shot#1140714031, which was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, JFT-2M shaped plasma that exhibited a WCM with approximately ~1 MA of J-antenna power. The 2015 version of the discharge (D+E antenna in place of J) did not exhibit a strong WCM, however. Moreover, it transitioned to an ELMy H-mode late in the shot. We backed off the RF power, reduced density and applied NINJA puffs in preparation for taking GPI and GP-CXRS (shot#4). The WCM was absent and the NINJA puffs resulted in a large density rise after 1.2 seconds. The G-H limiter also was showing some heat on the thermocouple display. On top of this, Dan found that the ASP-MLP was being corrupted by RF pickup, and unless we found a solution for this, the primary MP was in danger of being scrubbed. Shots 5 through 9 were spent exploring solutions. First we tried putting a 0.02s notch into the RF power programming at the time of ASP-MLP scan. This helped but did not eliminate the RF pickup problem and it affected (eliminated) whatever hint we had of a WCM response at the time of RF notch. At the same time, we increased the outer gap by 5 mm to avoid excessing G-H limiter heating and fiddled with the lower x-point position programming (RXL) to keep the plasma from leaning too hard on the inner divertor nose, potentially explaining some disruptions. Weak WCMs were seen that evolved with increasing RF power to a higher frequency fluctuation, punctuated with ELMs with a plasma density rise (H-mode like). Then we tried heating with D-antenna only, followed by heating with E-antenna only to see if the RF pickup problem on the ASP-MLP could be blamed on one or the other. Amazing, the answer was yes â?? D-antenna was generating the problem for the MLP. All the while, the NINJA puff was turned off to eliminate this as a variable. It remained off for the rest of the run as we could not justify turning it on given the fickleness of the WCM and the variability of the discharge. By shot#10 we had some partial solutions: MLP was collecting data without RF pickup (using E-antenna only), G-H limiter remained cool. But we still had weak WCMs with ELMs, evolving with a gentle RF power ramp (0.6 to 0.8 MW). Although not ideal, we decided to spend shots 13-16 getting the MLP as deep as possible into the â??modeâ??, achieving a scan to ~ 100 eV on shot#16. But, most of what the MLP saw was strong ELMs. Fluctuation spectra from the MLP did not pick up the feeble ~ 300 kHz mode. So either this WCM exists inside this zone and/or it is just not very strong in the region accessed by the probe. Further analysis will be needed. Anyway, not satisfied, we decided to try to eliminate/reduce the ELMs (and perhaps make the WCM more robust) by providing stability â?? shaping the crown of the plasma more like that of a standard discharge. A scan in ZXU programming was performed on shots 17-20. This idea proved to be worth pursuing. Shot#18 had the best WCM of the run. On shots 19 and 20 we overdid the ZXU tweak, resulting in ELMy H-modes. So on shot 21 and for the remainder of the run, we used shot#18 programming. From this point on, we starting â??multitaskingâ?? the discharge, scanning the MLP at 0.85 seconds to interrogate the â??improvedâ?? WCM, turning on/conditioning LHRF from 1 to 1.2 seconds and looking at the plasma response, and turning on the shoelace antenna on a few shots. By shot#26 we had some good MLP profiles of the â??improved WCMâ??, but still, the primary feature that we saw was ELMs. A first glance, spectra do not appear to show a strong WCM response. Again, we will need to comb through these data to see if there is any hint of a WCM. For discharges in which significant LHRF power was delivered, fluctuation spectra and overall plasma behavior was clearly affected â?? sometimes eliminating the WCM and other times bringing it back (see logbook notes). Shots 27-31 were spent setting up a vertical scan of the plasma position to provide data on the up/down asymmetry of the WCM. The MLP was not scanning on these shots. This did not prove easy and we ended up reloading shot#18 for shot#29, allowing LHRF to poke at it from 1.2 to 1.4 s. Shots#30 and 31 were attempts at a zcurr ramp-up and ramp-down, respectively, with the density programmed lower on the last shot. Unfortunately, the WCM did not repeat very well on these shots. But, LHRF clearly showed its influence on the last two discharges, affecting plasma density response and WCM response. Interesting shots for the scrapbook and further study.
It was a very interesting and successful run overall. Thanks everyone!

Session Leader Summary: MP826, â??Documenting high-performance ELM-free plasmasâ?
The purpose of this MP was to:
1. reproduce the fine ELM-free performance that was observed on 1160809011 and 014. 2. document physics of that regime 3. explore the parameter space open to the regime 4. extend duration of regime especially by reducing Prad
Technically, the machine operated extremely well. We lost an hour in the morning due to vibration issues in the alternator, and then a little while for a CPCI board problem. But then we ran ~22 plasmas with no disruptions, no fizzles, no duds. The RF performance was fantastic. We did three periods of successful between-shots boronization.
The short synopsis of this summary is that we did not complete step 1, which was a precondition to moving on to the other steps. We did not reproduce the high temperature (7.8 keV) on 1160809014, although we got to 6+ on some shots. Nor did we get the high H98.
I will post a detailed summary tomorrow. A few highlights are below:
1. The cryopump makes no difference to the performance today. We turned it off early.
2.Neon puffing did not reduce Prad and did not improve performance.
3.Increasing the RF power to 3.2 MW caused a much more rapid rise in Prad and a shorter H-mode duration before radiative collapse.
4. Decreasing the RF power to 1.8 MW prevented formation of the I-mode.
5. Between-shots boronization did reduce radiation to some extent, in fact one post-boronization shot got slightly lower Prad than the trophy shot 1160809014. Generally, the density was a little higher in the first post-boronization shot, but by the second shot it was down to pre-boronization levels (need to check that assertion).
6. We varied the pre-RF density from 4.e19 to 5.e19. This did not seem to make much difference.
7. We varied the timing of the ssep waveform, this did have an effect on the time required to go into H-mode, but did not generate the favorable conditions on 1160809014.
8. Early we tried delaying the change in ssep (to values close to zero) and this resulted in rather reproducible timing of the H-mode transition, but yet again, no performance like 1160809014.

As of shot # 1160830010 the total neutron production for the run is 1.03e+14 based on totals from the He3 neutron detectors The level of 1 x 10^14 neutrons is the threshold for posting this alert, and we have already reached that level. We expect to see mild activation of materials in ports following the run. Therefore, the following precautions should be taken if you need to work in the cell after the run:
1. Wear your radiation badge. 2. Borrow a survey meter from the desk near CmodWS65 and check for activity in the area where you want to work. Please return the meter when you are done!!! (Typically, the maximum value that we see on this meter is around 500 to 1000 cps, which is a few mRem per hour.) 3. Be especially wary of G-10 and aluminum structures.
The half-lives of most of the isotopes we produce are fairly short, so if you can delay any work until tomorrow morning, please do so.

As mentioned in the SL Summary, the machine ran extremely well today. The startup was equally robust with or without the cryopump. We stopped using the cryopump early in the run so that we could do the between shots boronizations.
The boronizations were done with the location fixed at 80 cm. This location was clearly shown by Bruce in 2007 to be the best location (1070612). We boronized for 10 and 20 minutes. 10 minutes seemed the best in terms of the improved performance, but other effects may have been involved. Other parameters:
pressure 35 mTorr ecrh power was pulsed no vertical field (unlike the 2007 runs) 10% borane
While using the cryopump I did drop the prefill to 11 ms following the boronization and then raised it again to 17 ms after one or two discharges.
In our attempts to regain the 1160809011,014 performance we boronized, modified the ZCUR programming, scanned the density, and puffed various gasses. Shot 13, following a 10 minute boronization, may have been our best shot, but it was no match to the 1160809 performance.
The EF1 commutation problem was "fixed" by cycling power to the cabinets.
Problems --------
We lost about 1 hour due to startup problems with the alternator.
We lost about 30 minutes fixing a crate/data system issue.

Session Leader plan for 8/30/2016 MP826: Documenting high-performance ELM-free plasmas
Note: this run may involve between-shots boronization.
The purpose of this experiment is to:
1. Reproduce the very high performance in ELM-free H-modes that was observed on shot 1160809014.
2. Document that plasma carefully with HIREX, CXRS, LBO, GPI and the usual turbulence measurements.
3. Explore the parameter space available to this regime (Ip, RF power, ssep)
4. Reduce the radiated power (impurity gas puff, or between-shots boronization) and extend the period before radiative collapse (ssep ramp).
5. If time permits, add LH to see if we can develop a true AT regime plasma.
Experiemental sequence:
1. Re-establish 1160809014 and recover from ECDC (3 shots)
2. Take a duplicate shot, but without the cryopump. Purpose is to determine whether or not the cryopump is needed to get the transition to ELM-free H-mode (1 shot)
3. Document 1160809014 look-alike with HIREX (including a locked-mode shot), then CXRS, LBO and GPI. Note that LBO can go piggyback once we have the condition well-established, and slowly increase the injected Ca amount shot-by-shot until either they get enough signal for a good measurement, or until the injected amount perturbs the plasma (7 shots)
4. Low-Z gas seeding to control Prad (2-3 shots). If this proves successful, we will continue to use it on subsequent shots.
5. Between-shots boronization (2-5 shots). Determine if boronization kills access to the ELM-free regime and whether it helps to reduce Prad, thereby extending the duration of the period of favorable confinement.
6. Parameter scan: vary ssep in I-mode that precedes the ELM-free regime, to determine the ssep parameter space available to this regime. (2 shots)
7. Vary RF power. Both simple increases and step-up in time (3-4 shots).
8. Increase Ip to 1.0 then to 1.1 or 1.2 MA.
9. Adjust outer gap to enable robust LH current drive, and inject LH at n_parallel of 2.3 to drive current.
10. Ip ramps following the transition to ELM-free regime.
Note: there are some decision points along the way. There are several critical issues that affect the run-day strategy:
1. Do we observe the transition to ELM-free H-mode at all?
2. Is the onset time of the transition reproducible? If not, we will need to reassess the strategy/priority of studies that involve perturbations that occur at some fixed time relative to entering the regime.
3. Is the cryopump needed for the transition? If yes, then we cannot do between-shots boronization. If not, we will warm up the cryopump to allow for eventual between-shots boronization.
4. If we elect not to do boronization, then we might be able to do the final study involving LH. But if we do boronize, then we'll postpone the LH shot to another day.

The purpose of todayâ??s run (MP826) was to recover the high performance observed in 1160809014 mostly by reducing radiated power and reducing moly content. We tried N2 puffing via the NINJA system early in the day, that did not seem to help control radiated power, although there is a hint (needs to be evaluated carefully) that the edge Te values were higher than yesterday. Then we tried changing the strike location, that did not materially affect the time development of Prad either. On the last shot (12) we put in a considerable amount of N2 from 0.55 to 0.65 sec. Interestingly, while caused a big reduction in moly, the rate of rise of Prad following the transition to ELM-free H-mode (which was delayed relative to the othershots) was nearly identical to the earlier shots. So it looks as if the additional radiation from N2 exactly balances the reduction from moly, and to make matters worse the radiative collapse occurred earlier. l1160831005:
Dud. EF3 failed. But we did change the strike point.
We lost about 45 minutes at the start of the day due alternator vibration issues, and we lost one shot due to an EF3 problem. Otherwise, the run went smoothly. RF performed great.
Shots 3, 4, 6, 9 and 10 are extremely similar, including the onset time of the ELM-free H-mode. The time history of Prad following the start of the H-mode is very similar. Shots 2 and 11 are also similar to the first set, except that the transition time to ELM-free H-mode is delayed a little. Shot 12 also has a delayed onset time of the H-mode but more importantly, it experiences radiative collapse earlier than the other shots.

MP 802: Ohmic and low-power L-mode sawteeth as probes of perturbative heat transport
Overview: The goals of this set of experiments were fairly straight forward - keep densityt fixed, change the RF power to increase the temperature and sawtooth amplitude. If time permits, repeat at different densities. From these data we (I) will attempt to derive a measure the thermal diffusivity. These values will be examined for dependence on crash amplitude, mean temperature, density, and ultimately compared against TRANSP runs.
Comments on the run: The machine ran well, but not flawlessly given our relatively humble requests. I think the gods approved of the olives, tomatos and bread, but were probably somewhat irritated that I did not provide them with herring as well. We had two densities and a nice set of RF powers for each, ohmic + 100,300,500,750,1000 for the first one, and ohmic + 500, 1000 for the second. This should provide us some good data for heat pulse analysis.
Saeid seemed happy with the Bt jogs as well and is planning in using this new data to further develop his new MP for submission at the next EPC.

This will be a continuation of MP826 that was run on 1160830 (first half day)
Technical changes from setup on 1160830:
1. cryopump will be off and warm. 2. N2 in C and F Ninja 3. We want to retain the capability to do between-shots boronization, but at the present time we do not think that boronization is the magic bullet and so the probability of between-shots boronization is less than 50%.
The run on 1160830 was technically a fantastic success, but alas we were unable to reproduce the very high performance ELM-free shot 1160809014.
Remaining things to try:
1. Puff N2 late in the shot, so that there is residual N2 in the subsequent shot. This is based not so much on science but superstition: there was N2 puffing on 1160809.
2. There is a thought process about the evolution of the shot 1160809014 that says the key is getting a very hot I-mode that precedes the H-mode. So do do this, we will (a) keep ssep a little more negative during the initial period of RF heating, and (b) at the same time, increase the heating power. Then, after a hot I-mode is formed, increase ssep (i.e. close to zero) and at the same time drop the RF power.
3. Make adjustments to the strike points in an effort to reduce Prad without the use of between-shots boronization.
4. Possibly, increase Ip to 1.0 MA and BT to 6.0 Tesla, in an effort to increase Te in the I-mode phase. What needs to be defined here is what RF power level to use.

Remaining things to try:

So do do this, we will (a) keep ssep a little more negative during the initial period of RF heating, and (b) at the same time, increase the heating power. Then, after a hot I-mode is formed, increase ssep (i.e. close to zero) and at the same time drop the RF power.
3. Conversely, ramp ICRF up during the ELM-free H-mode. Motivation: Even if it doesn't change the H-factor, you should get to higher temperatures which should marginally reduce the radiating efficiency of the impurities faster than increasing the source. As of shot # 1160831012 the total neutron production for the run is 1.09e+14 based on totals from the He3 neutron detectors The level of 1 x 10^14 neutrons is the threshold for posting this alert, and we have already reached that level. We expect to see mild activation of materials in ports following the run. Therefore, the following precautions should be taken if you need to work in the cell after the run:
1. Wear your radiation badge. 2. Borrow a survey meter from the desk near CmodWS65 and check for activity in the area where you want to work. Please return the meter when you are done!!! (Typically, the maximum value that we see on this meter is around 500 to 1000 cps, which is a few mRem per hour.) 3. Be especially wary of G-10 and aluminum structures.
The half-lives of most of the isotopes we produce are fairly short, so if you can delay any work until tomorrow morning, please do so.

------------------ MP 802 ------------------ Ohmic and low-power L-mode sawteeth as probes of perturbative heat transport
Purpose: To explore the heat pulse propagation from sawteeth in ohmic and low power RF-heated plasmas. Heat pulses from very small sawteeth have been shown to exhibit near diffusive transport, suggesting that there may be an amplitude dependence in the hyper diffusion observed in strong RF or beam heated plasmas observed previously. We aim to examine this effect more closely by changing the ICRF power in an attempt to change the sawtooth size.
------------------ Machine Parameters ------------------ Equilibrium: 1160804021 Toroidal Field: 5.3 T *see note below Plasma Current: 0.8 MA Working Gas: D2 Density: nl_04 ~0.4x10^20 m^-2 Boronization: no
note: The toroidal field should be reduced to 5.3 Tesla. We are going to add a Bt job so that Saied can piggy-back on this run.
Jog plan (all shots): 5.3 T to 1.2 sec ramp to 5.4 T over 100 msec starting at 1.2 sec idle at 5.4 T for 100 msec ramp to 5.3 T over 100 msec starting at 1.4 sec current ramp down starting at 1.55 sec
------------------ Auxiliary Systems ------------------ ICRF Power: 1 MW, use J in 2-strap configuration LHCD Power: no LBO: no DNB: no Gas: H-bottom with 1 psi Ar (HIREX), enabled NINJA C-port 7 psi He (GPI) NINJA F-port 8 psi D2 (CXRS) Cryopump: yes Non-axisymmetric Coils: standard configuration
------------------ Diagnostics ------------------ Absolutely necessary: FRCECE, ECE, Hirex, Thomson
Nice to have: CECE PCI Reflectometer GPI Bolometers and diodes CXRS TCI Polarimeter
------------------ Run plan ------------------ 1. Establish target shot using 1160804021, with B-field modified to 5.3 Tesla as noted above.
2. Extra shot to refine target density to 0.4 to 0.45 (nl_04).
3-6. Same but increase ICRF by 100 kW each shot.
7. Locked mode shot for Hirex, use 1160826008.
8-10. Increase ICRF by 200 kW (to 1.0 MW).
11-15. Increase density to 0.7x10^20, ICRF power of 0, 100, 200, 300, 400 kW.
We can do more if time allows.

PO Summary for 1160831 PO: G. Wallace
The day started with a delay for the alternator. First shot got off around 09:50.
During the morning half of the run we picked up where we left off yesterday afternoon. We ran without the cryopump in case between shot boronization was needed, however we didn't end up boronizing so this was unnecessary. Ultimately we were unable to replicate the very high performance results from 1160809014. Playing with the strike points did not solve impurity generation issues, nor did puffing of N2.
The second half of the day was low power L-modes which worked fairly well, except for a string of locked modes and subsequent disruptions. The locked modes were fixed by adding feedforward gas puffing in the early part of seg 2.
No issues on startup without cryopump (AM) or with cryopump (PM).
Two duds today, one on shot 5 (EF3) and another on shot 22 (OH2). Also no power shot on 25.

Plan for first half of run.
MP#750 - Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe
Background/Goal: The MLP has demonstrated the ability to resolve the mode structure of a 110 kHz Quasi-Coherent Mode (QCM), directly recording time series snapshots (1.1 MHz sampling rate) of density, electron temperature and plasma potential in the mode layer on multiple electrodes. These measurements have allowed the relative phase angles among these quantities to be resolved and the phase propagation velocity in the plasma frame to be deduced by simultaneously recording the electric field in the mode layer (i.e., accounting for ExB plasma motion). The goal of this MP is to perform similar measurements of the WCM.
Diagnostics: - Horizontal probe (ASP) with Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) system connected. The standard Langmuir-Mach probe head must be installed on the A-port drive system. This is the most robust head for high heat flux. - Reflectometer - GPI fast-diode system (may need to change outer gap to accommodate this diagnostic at the risk of altering the 'magic' of the plasma shape in obtaining these low power WCM conditions - need to assess during run time.) - Phase contrast imaging - Fast Mirnov coils - Edge Thomson scattering
Gas Setup: NINJA C-port: 10 PSI He for GPI NINJA F-port: 7 PSI He
ICRF: Yes. Prepare for about 1 MW from D or E or J DNB: no LH: no Cryopump: Yes Overnight ECDC: standard parameters
Reload 1140714031. This was an 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, NL04 ~ 0.5E20, JFT-2M-shaped discharge with 1 MW RF (J-ant) and a very nice WCM. This plasma disrupted at 1.4 seconds, however, so it may need some attention.
Step 1 - Establish 0.8 MA low power I-mode 5.4 tesla, 0.8 MA, NL04 ~ 0.6 x10^20m^-2 discharge but with RF power ramp from 0.5 to 1.0 MW from 0.7 to 1.0 seconds and holding at 1.0 MW until 1.3 seconds. Track onset time of I-mode and WCM and reduce max RF power if possible while maintaining I-mode and WCM.
Note: getting the outer strikepoint on the EF1 shelf is very important. Overlay the flux contours with 1140714031 and modify if necessary for a good match.
Step 2 - Target WCM with MLP Optimize probe timing and increase plunge depth of probe shot-by-shot in an attempt to scan through the mode layer. Optimize gas puffs for GPI and GP-charge exchange systems so as to sample WCM just after probe insertion time.

Nano-proposal based on MP693: two shots reserved for an Ip-ramp to validate MSE's ability to follow changes in the pitch-angle profile. Our old reference shot 1120516021 is deemed too old and decrepit by the PO, so we will work from recent shot 1160927027.
1. extend Bt flattop to 1.7 sec. 2. Raise Ip to 0.9 MA at t=0.3, keep Ip constant at 0.9 until t=0.45, then ramp Ip down linearly in time until it reaches 0.2 MA at t=1.7 sec. 3. keep NL04 demand constant at 0.6e20 throughout the Ip ramp.
No RF, no LH, no argon puff, no cryopump.

==General observations: Ip= 820kA then ramps down to 520 kA from 0.85 to 1.0s. Rampdown at 1.50s LH turn on at 0.7s off at 1.4s, 700kW @ 90deg Fault at 1.1s nel04=0.25 to 0.3 PLH/nebar = 1100 to 1500 Upper null
The loop voltage prior to LH was 1.2V and steady LH pushes the loop voltage down to 0.15V The current ramp pushes it further, across zero When the current ramp stops the loop voltage results at the value it was prior to the ramp. LH turns off and the loop voltage goes to 0.95V prior to turn off
The current ramp down decreases the HXR count rates and ECE non-thermal emission significantly despite having nearly the same PLH/nebar and relatively constant density during this time.
There is MHD on the xtomo system, fishbone like, at 0.99 to 1.02s. This is during the current ramp and LHCD simultaneously. Thoug hit does not appear that this corresponds to any large signals on the other indicators of LHCD as it is a short burst and the other trends are longer.
Sawteeth start at 0.27s. Then they are suppressed at 0.86, approximately 60ms after LH starts. This is just about the time the plasma current ramps down. But the sawteeth are very nearly gone before this. They get very small starting at 0.8s. Then when LH faults off there are two small sawteeth at 1.1s just prior to LH turning on which then suppresses them again immediately. After LH turns off the sawteeth resume at 1.4s, almost immediately after LH shuts off.
The beam was fired for 7 pulses at 42kV and 5.5 to 6.5A. One pulse had nasty faulting. This was effectively the last shot of the beam in C-Mod's lifetime.

NINJA Set up to puff He from AB_lim (411 Torr) trigger at 1.0 s (duration 0.08 s) gas hits at 1.146 s GPI sees both the WCM and a strong 10 kHz GAM and a harmonic(?) of the GAM on columns 0,1,2 (GAM still on col 3) (0 is innermost) (1.17 thru 1.39 s) Probably a trophy shot for GAM. These are I-modes in the JFT2M shape. The GAM is very large and the WCM was very broad in freq. See shots 1160929011 (at anytime between 1.17-1.39s), shot 010 (at anytime between 1.17-1.39s), shot 014 (at anytime between 1.095-1.23s), shot 016 (between 1.15-1.19s), shot 017 (between 1.05-1.99s). The 10 kHz fluctuational is huge in the signal. What is that double feature (harmonic)? Istvan notes that: "They may not both be GAM. In any case, a "GAM proper" cannot cause any radial transport, as it is a radial electrostatic mode. The best it can do is modulate transport by shearing certain turbulent structures or eating up their free energy. If we have some other low frequency beast excited, that's a different story (and may explain how it can have such a large amplitude even in the density fluctuations!)" These fluctuations are so big that they are seen on the divertor probes, resulting in speculation that they alone are responsible for the particle pumpout in I-mode.

Session Leader Run Summary - First Half of 1160929
MP#750 â?? "Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe"
Primary Goal: Establish a discharge with a weakly coherent mode (WCM) under low power conditions (~ 1 MW ICRF) using "JFT-2M" plasma shaping; use the A-port scanning Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) diagnostic to interrogate its mode structure in detail -- if the mode exists sufficiently close to the last closed flux surface that the probe can reach it.
Result: This was a productive run. We reloaded shot#1140714031, which was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, JFT-2M shaped plasma that exhibited a WCM with approximately ~1.2 MW of RF (D+E). For some reason we encountered some early injections and runaways leading to early terminations. But by shot#6 we started to get a shaped matched to the target shot. By shot#10 we got shots with a strong GAM (10 kHz) and a weak WCM, but in any case we had no choice but to proceed with pushing in the scanning probe. Shots 11, 12, 14 and 16 were useful with GPI and CXRS and the best scanning probe data were obtained on 14 and 16. Cross-comparisons between GPI and CXRS were performed to help localize the mode location with respect to these diagnostics.
The GAM was very intense on 60 GHz reflectometer and the ASP-MLP on shots#14 and 16, appearing as a fluctuation with amplitude of 2 amperes(!) in ion saturation current. The 10 kHz GAM was seen around the 50 eV location, indicating that it is a monster amplitude mode that spans the LCFS. We were not able to poke the probe much beyond the LCFS so we wonâ??t be able to say anything about its radial extent using the ASP-MLP. The â??GAMâ?? fluctuations were also detected on inner divertor probes, which is a strong indication that this mode is not simply a GAM â?? it leads to particle flux in the SOL. Perhaps this is the mode (and not the WCM) that is the reason for the low I-mode particle and impurity confinement. If so the story parallels that of the QCM and EDA H-modes:
EDA H-mode: QCM is a drift-like mode that spans the LCFS and drives radially outward particle fluxes
I-Mode: A â??GAMâ?? - like mode spans the LCFS and drives radially outward particle fluxes. This latter statement needs to be verified by analysis of the fluctuation recorded by the ASP-MLP. Also, we might be able to say something about the mode structure â?? drift-wave like with regard to density and potential phase angles? Phase velocity in the plasma frame?
In both these situations, the mode occurs at the base of the pedestal, at low Te values. So even though the modes can drive out significant particle flux, it does not result in a large convected energy flux.
We did detect some high frequency fluctuations on the ASP-MLP, probably associated with the WCM. So there is a lot to chew on.
Thanks everyone for making these measurements possible!

Session Leader Run Summary - First Half of 1160929
MP#750 -- "Investigation of the mode structure of the WCM with a scanning Mirror Langmuir probe"
Primary Goal: Establish a discharge with a weakly coherent mode (WCM) under low power conditions (~ 1 MW ICRF) using "JFT-2M" plasma shaping; use the A-port scanning Mirror Langmuir Probe (MLP) diagnostic to interrogate its mode structure in detail -- if the mode exists sufficiently close to the last closed flux surface that the probe can reach it.
Result: This was a productive run. We reloaded shot#1140714031, which was a 0.8 MA, 5.4 tesla, JFT-2M shaped plasma that exhibited a WCM with approximately ~1.2 MW of RF (D+E). For some reason we encountered some early injections and runaways leading to early terminations. But by shot#6 we started to get a shaped matched to the target shot. By shot#10 we got shots with a strong GAM (10 kHz) and a weak WCM, but in any case we had no choice but to proceed with pushing in the scanning probe. Shots 11, 12, 14 and 16 were useful with GPI and CXRS and the best scanning probe data were obtained on 14 and 16. Cross-comparisons between GPI and CXRS were performed to help localize the mode location with respect to these diagnostics.
The GAM was very intense on 60 GHz reflectometer and the ASP-MLP on shots#14 and 16, appearing as a fluctuation with amplitude of 2 amperes(!) in ion saturation current. The 10 kHz GAM was seen around the 50 eV location, indicating that it is a monster amplitude mode that spans the LCFS. We were not able to poke the probe much beyond the LCFS so we won't be able to say anything about its radial extent using the ASP-MLP. The 'GAM' fluctuations were also detected on inner divertor probes, which is a strong indication that this mode is not simply a GAM -- it leads to particle flux in the SOL. Perhaps this is the mode (and not the WCM) that is the reason for the low I-mode particle and impurity confinement. If so the story parallels that of the QCM and EDA H-modes:
EDA H-mode: QCM is a drift-like mode that spans the LCFS and drives radially outward particle fluxes
I-Mode: A 'GAM' - like mode spans the LCFS and drives radially outward particle fluxes. This latter statement needs to be verified by analysis of the fluctuation recorded by the ASP-MLP. Also, we might be able to say something about the mode structure -- drift-wave like with regard to density and potential phase angles? Phase velocity in the plasma frame?
In both these situations, the mode occurs at the base of the pedestal, at low Te values. So even though the modes can drive out significant particle flux, it does not result in a large convected energy flux.
We did detect some high frequency fluctuations on the ASP-MLP, probably associated with the WCM. So there is a lot to chew on.
Thanks everyone for making these measurements possible!

Draft SL_Plan for Friday, Sep 30, 2016
MP#813 "EDA Access at 8 tesla"
SL: wolfe
PO: hutch,marmar

This run aims to complete the high current portion of MP#813, trying to access
the 8T EDA at as high a current (and low q95) as possible. The half-run on
1160729 succeeded in reaching 1.4MA, q95=3.8 on shot#8, but that was the only
successful H-mode shot of the day. The main problem seemed to be keeping the
RF on, and getting decent heating efficiency. THat shot did reach ~200kJ with
P_rf~3.8MW. We will start by trying to reproduce that shot, then increase
current to 1.6MW.

Shot#8 actually has a very negative SSEP and a decreasing elongation, down to
1.55 or so by 1.2sec. Probably want to try higher elongation and closer to DN,
allowing even higher Ip, up to 1.7MA anyway, maybe higher. 

Setup:
-------
Overnight boronization required. Standard prescription. 
Post-boronization ECDC in He, as long as we can get but at least two
hours. Might consider not starting the run until 9:00 in order to get more
ECDC, especially if we are planning to go past 18:00 anyway.  

Engineering Setup:
-----------------
Cryopump on for first shot (may decide to turn it off later?)

Gas setup:
     B-top          6psi D2 ENABLED
     B-main        40psi D2 ENABLED
     B-side Lower   2psi Ar DISABLED
     B-side Upper  as is He3 Disabled for Step 0, ENABLE for all 7.8T shots
     H-Bot         40psi D2 DISABLED (may need for additional fueling at
                                      higher currents)
     B-DIV         20psi N2 DISABLED (for seeding, if needed)
     H-DIV         as is    DISABLED

     NINJA C-port  8psi He DISABLED (for GPI)
     NINJA F-port 10psi D2 DISABLED for CXRS &inboard) 
                                    May use for additional inboard fueling at
                                    higher Ip. 
Engineering Power System Setup
-------------------------------

Step 0: As on 1160808001 (5.4T)
Step 1-N: As on 1160729008 (7.8T), alternator to 1716 rpm
  

Shot Sequence
--------------

0) Boronization recovery: No idea yet what to do for this. The RF is different
enough at 5.4T it's not clear if we save any time doing it there. On the
initial run on this MP on 1160708 we took 10 shots at 5.4T to recover. [5-10
shots @5.4T], 1-2.5 hours. 

0.a) Load from 1160708001 (5.4T, 800kA, sweeping strikes up and down the vertical
plate. Run up to 5 shots to get RF steady, reduce RF "fueling". Exercise Argon
valve at the end of at least one shot, then turn off. [1-5 shots]

0.b) Run locked mode shot, e.g. 1160725013 or lm shot from Wednesday morning
[1-2 shots]

0.c) If it appears necessary, run intentional disruption to reduce neutral
pressure, RF "fueling" effect. Move ZCUR sharply down and turn off ZCUR3 gains
at 1.0sec [0-1 shot]

0.d) Continue RF recovery, as needed [0-3 shots]

1) Reload from 1160729008 (7.8T, 1.4MA). Turn off argon puff (we've already
got HIREX data on this one). Attempt to reproduce this shot with as much power
as RF can manage. Adjust B-side Upper (He3) puff based on PCI data (probably
down to 100 or 125msec from 150ms. [2-3 shots], 1-1.5 hours.
  Note: PO should update dpcs_lowpass_obs to apply to wires [10,14] segs
  [2,3,4] and consider raising P,D and reducing PG3 feedforward, at least
  by Step #2.
  
2) Increase Ip from 1.4 to 1.6MA, aiming for q95~3.3 . Increase NL04 target to
1.6e20. Depending on whether Step 1 was better than the reference shot,
consider turning Argon back on. This step is the first new thing for this day.
Adjust RF waveforms, He3 puff (guided by PCI results) to get into EDA,
increase power to max possible during EDA. Consider seeding, changing
strikepoint sweeps, gaps, to reduce Mo influx (if it's a problem) 
[1-5 shots], 0.5-2.5 hours
 
3) Increase elongation, decrease SSEP. Aim for kappa=1.7, SSEP=-5mm Evaluate
change in q95, cryopumping, neutral pressuure, RF coupling, Wmhd. 
 [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

4) Increase Ip again, aiming to get back to q95~3.2 or so, with the higher
elongation. Expect this will be about 1.7 or 1.8MA, nl04 target to
1.8e20. [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

5) Depending on the time, and whatever is decided to do next, push toward
2MA, q95<3. Or push it up to DN, if that looks more promising.

<pre> Sensitivity calibration of the midplane Phantom GPI system:
After the 2016 campaign Sean Ballinger and I used the diode-based "new" Labsphere to do a sensitivity calibration of the midplane system and the Phantom camera. We did not clean or touch the optics, so these calibrations represent the state of the system with dirty/browned optics. We calibrated the system with 3 interference filters a) "old HeI-5876 (AC-J141-02)" b) "old D_a-6563 (H234-101)" c) "new D_a-6563 (J091-02)"
We did not calibrate with the "new HeI-5876 A (AM-446701)" filter. I took the following test shots, each with a framerate of 800 fps for 1000 frames. The integration times were varied as noted and a new session reference was taken for each new setting.
shot # light/no light filter integration time (us) counts/s 1161122903 light "old HeI-5876" 500 5.75e5 1161122904 no light "old HeI-5876" 500 0.53e5 1161122905 light "old HeI-5876" 1200 5.21e5 1161122906 no light "old HeI-5876" 1200 0.048e5 1161122907 light "old HeI-5876" 1200 5.24e5 1161122908 no light "old HeI-5876" 1200 0.050e5
1161122909 light "old D_a-6563" 1200 22.2e5 1161122910 no light "old D_a-6563" 1200 0.034e5 1161122911 no light "old D_a-6563" 500 0.67e5 1161122912 light "old D_a-6563" 500 23.6e5 1161122913 light "old D_a-6563" 500 23.5e5 1161122914 no light "old D_a-6563" 500 0.67e5
1161122915 light "new D_a-6563" 500 23.3e5 1161122916 no light "new D_a-6563" 500 0.60e5 1161122917 light "new D_a-6563" 500 23.3e5 1161122918 light "new D_a-6563" 500 23.3e5
I moved these shots from the test shot area to /cmod/trees/saved/spectroscopy/ area.
The diode current for the diode-calibrated Labsphere was 0.209e-6 amps when we started and was 0.211e-6 amps when we stopped. Thus the calibration values should be reduced by the ratio of diode currents, i.e. by a factor of 0.917. This is done by running /home/terry/h0/labsphere_brightness.pro and by noting that the diode-calibrated brightnesses at 587.6 nm and 656 nm are 3.71 uW/cm^2/ster/nm and 5.14 uW/cm^2/ster/nm respectively.
The filter bandpasses have to be measured (perhaps see Logbook entry from 1110519).

SL_Plan for Friday, Sep 30, 2016
MP#813 "EDA Access at 8 tesla"
SL: wolfe
PO: hutch,marmar

This run aims to complete the high current portion of MP#813, trying to access
the 8T EDA at as high a current (and low q95) as possible. The half-run on
1160729 succeeded in reaching 1.4MA, q95=3.8 on shot#8, but that was the only
successful H-mode shot of the day. The main problem seemed to be keeping the
RF on, and getting decent heating efficiency. THat shot did reach ~200kJ with
P_rf~3.8MW. We will start by trying to reproduce that shot, then increase
current to 1.6MW.

Shot#8 actually has a very negative SSEP and a decreasing elongation, down to
1.55 or so by 1.2sec. Probably want to try higher elongation and closer to DN,
allowing even higher Ip, up to 1.7MA anyway, maybe higher.

-------
Overnight boronization required. Standard prescription. 
Post-boronization ECDC in He, as long as we can get but at least two
hours. Start ECDC as soon as possible after completion of bzn (120psi)

Shot Sequence
--------------

0) Boronization recovery: No idea yet what to do for this. The RF is different
enough at 5.4T it's not clear if we save any time doing it there. On the
initial run on this MP on 1160708 we took 10 shots at 5.4T to recover. To
reproduce the same sequence, the starting point 1160708001 would be
appropriate. 
 
It has been suggested that these shots be used for discharge development for
upside-down forward field Super H-mode experiment based on 1150722032. Rather
than attempt to do all the field reversals, flips, and time reversals on this
example, I would suggest starting from an USN forward-field I-mode case and
bringing up the lower xpoint and ZCUR to make it closse to DN (upper) and then
introduce a downward move to transition to LSN. Possible starting point for
this could be 1160617017. 
Allocation for step 0: [5-10 shots @5.4T], 1-2.5 hours. 

0.a) Load from 1160708001 (5.4T, 800kA) OR
MP830 development shot from Jerry: /home/jwhughes/physop/pcs_scratch/ 
  #1160930234

Implement  sweeping strikes up and down the vertical
plate. Run up to 5 shots to get RF steady, reduce RF "fueling". Exercise Argon
valve at the end of at least one shot, then turn off. [1-5 shots]

0.b) Run locked mode shot, e.g. 1160725013 or lm shot from Wednesday morning
[1-2 shots]

0.c) If it appears necessary, run intentional disruption to reduce neutral
pressure, RF "fueling" effect. Move ZCUR sharply down and turn off ZCUR3 gains
at 1.0sec [0-1 shot]

0.d) Continue RF recovery, as needed [0-3 shots]

1) Reload from 1160729008 (7.8T, 1.4MA). Turn off argon puff (we've already
got HIREX data on this one). Attempt to reproduce this shot with as much power
as RF can manage. Adjust B-side Upper (He3) puff based on PCI data (probably
down to 100 or 125msec from 150ms. [2-3 shots], 1-1.5 hours.
  Note: PO should update dpcs_lowpass_obs to apply to wires [10,14] segs
  [2,3,4] and consider raising P,D and reducing PG3 feedforward, at least
  by Step #2.
  
2) Increase Ip from 1.4 to 1.6MA, aiming for q95~3.3 . Increase NL04 target to
1.6e20. Depending on whether Step 1 was better than the reference shot,
consider turning Argon back on. This step is the first new thing for this day.
Adjust RF waveforms, He3 puff (guided by PCI results) to get into EDA,
increase power to max possible during EDA. Consider seeding, changing
strikepoint sweeps, gaps, to reduce Mo influx (if it's a problem).
If RF power is insufficient to get L-H at the higher density, then try going
to step 3 (higher kappa, closer to DN), maybe up to SSEP > -1mm, to take
advantage of the "sweet spot"  at DN. Alternatively, start in the LSN slot,
then sweep onto the vertical plate. 
Step 2: [1-5 shots], 0.5-2.5 hours
 
3) Increase elongation, decrease SSEP. Aim for kappa=1.7, SSEP=-5mm Evaluate
change in q95, cryopumping, neutral pressure, RF coupling, Wmhd. 
Step 3:  [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

4) Increase Ip again, aiming to get back to q95~3.2 or so, with the higher
elongation. Expect this will be about 1.7 or 1.8MA, nl04 target to
1.8e20. 
Step 4: [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

5) Depending on the time, and whatever is decided to do next, push toward
2MA, q95<3. Or push it up to DN, if that looks more promising. 

6) If/when we get to a point that further increases in current are not
compatible with EDA, or it gets to be 18:00, 
then move on to one of the alternate Run Plans for high
performance (ELM-free at high current, "Super H-mode" approach, Improvements
to 5.4T, 1.3MA case 1160718013, ...).

SL_Plan for Friday, Sep 30, 2016
MP#813 "EDA Access at 8 tesla"
SL: wolfe
PO: hutch,marmar

This run aims to complete the high current portion of MP#813, trying to access
the 8T EDA at as high a current (and low q95) as possible. The half-run on
1160729 succeeded in reaching 1.4MA, q95=3.8 on shot#8, but that was the only
successful H-mode shot of the day. The main problem seemed to be keeping the
RF on, and getting decent heating efficiency. THat shot did reach ~200kJ with
P_rf~3.8MW. We will start by trying to reproduce that shot, then increase
current to 1.6MW.

Shot#8 actually has a very negative SSEP and a decreasing elongation, down to
1.55 or so by 1.2sec. Probably want to try higher elongation and closer to DN,
allowing even higher Ip, up to 1.7MA anyway, maybe higher.

hours. Start ECDC as soon as possible after completion of bzn (120psi)

Shot Sequence
--------------

0) Boronization recovery: No idea yet what to do for this. The RF is different
enough at 5.4T it's not clear if we save any time doing it there. On the
initial run on this MP on 1160708 we took 10 shots at 5.4T to recover. To
reproduce the same sequence, the starting point 1160708001 would be
appropriate. 
 
It has been suggested that these shots be used for discharge development for
upside-down forward field Super H-mode experiment based on 1150722032. Rather
than attempt to do all the field reversals, flips, and time reversals on this
example, I would suggest starting from an USN forward-field I-mode case and
bringing up the lower xpoint and ZCUR to make it closse to DN (upper) and then
introduce a downward move to transition to LSN. Possible starting point for
this could be 1160617017. 
Allocation for step 0: [5-10 shots @5.4T], 1-2.5 hours. 

0.a) Load from 1160708001 (5.4T, 800kA) or MP830 development shot from Jerry. 
Implement  sweeping strikes up and down the vertical
plate. Run up to 5 shots to get RF steady, reduce RF "fueling". Exercise Argon
valve at the end of at least one shot, then turn off. [1-5 shots]

0.b) Run locked mode shot, e.g. 1160725013 or lm shot from Wednesday morning
[1-2 shots]

0.c) If it appears necessary, run intentional disruption to reduce neutral
pressure, RF "fueling" effect. Move ZCUR sharply down and turn off ZCUR3 gains
at 1.0sec [0-1 shot]

0.d) Continue RF recovery, as needed [0-3 shots]

1) Reload from 1160729008 (7.8T, 1.4MA). Turn off argon puff (we've already
got HIREX data on this one). Attempt to reproduce this shot with as much power
as RF can manage. Adjust B-side Upper (He3) puff based on PCI data (probably
down to 100 or 125msec from 150ms. [2-3 shots], 1-1.5 hours.
  Note: PO should update dpcs_lowpass_obs to apply to wires [10,14] segs
  [2,3,4] and consider raising P,D and reducing PG3 feedforward, at least
  by Step #2.
  
2) Increase Ip from 1.4 to 1.6MA, aiming for q95~3.3 . Increase NL04 target to
1.6e20. Depending on whether Step 1 was better than the reference shot,
consider turning Argon back on. This step is the first new thing for this day.
Adjust RF waveforms, He3 puff (guided by PCI results) to get into EDA,
increase power to max possible during EDA. Consider seeding, changing
strikepoint sweeps, gaps, to reduce Mo influx (if it's a problem).
If RF power is insufficient to get L-H at the higher density, then try going
to step 3 (higher kappa, closer to DN), maybe up to SSEP > -1mm, to take
advantage of the "sweet spot"  at DN. Alternatively, start in the LSN slot,
then sweep onto the vertical plate. 
Step 2: [1-5 shots], 0.5-2.5 hours
 
3) Increase elongation, decrease SSEP. Aim for kappa=1.7, SSEP=-5mm Evaluate
change in q95, cryopumping, neutral pressure, RF coupling, Wmhd. 
Step 3:  [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

4) Increase Ip again, aiming to get back to q95~3.2 or so, with the higher
elongation. Expect this will be about 1.7 or 1.8MA, nl04 target to
1.8e20. 
Step 4: [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

5) Depending on the time, and whatever is decided to do next, push toward
2MA, q95<3. Or push it up to DN, if that looks more promising. 

6) If/when we get to a point that further increases in current are not
compatible with EDA, or it gets to be 18:00, 
then move on to one of the alternate Run Plans for high
performance (ELM-free at high current, "Super H-mode" approach, Improvements
to 5.4T, 1.3MA case 1160718013, ...).

The rectifier unit that died is the one that is on the central horizontal board that is located beneath the top boards. As of shot # 1160930019 the total neutron production for the run is 1.06e+14 based on totals from the He3 neutron detectors The level of 1 x 10^14 neutrons is the threshold for posting this alert, and we have already reached that level. We expect to see mild activation of materials in ports following the run. Therefore, the following precautions should be taken if you need to work in the cell after the run:
1. Wear your radiation badge. 2. Borrow a survey meter from the desk near CmodWS65 and check for activity in the area where you want to work. Please return the meter when you are done!!! (Typically, the maximum value that we see on this meter is around 500 to 1000 cps, which is a few mRem per hour.) 3. Be especially wary of G-10 and aluminum structures.
The half-lives of most of the isotopes we produce are fairly short, so if you can delay any work until tomorrow morning, please do so.

MP#813 "EDA Access at 8 tesla"
SL: wolfe
PO: hutch,marmar

This run aims to complete the high current portion of MP#813, trying to access
the 8T EDA at as high a current (and low q95) as possible. The half-run on
1160729 succeeded in reaching 1.4MA, q95=3.8 on shot#8, but that was the only
successful H-mode shot of the day. The main problem seemed to be keeping the
RF on, and getting decent heating efficiency. THat shot did reach ~200kJ with
P_rf~3.8MW. We will start by trying to reproduce that shot, then increase
current to 1.6MW.

Shot#8 actually has a very negative SSEP and a decreasing elongation, down to
1.55 or so by 1.2sec. Probably want to try higher elongation and closer to DN,
allowing even higher Ip, up to 1.7MA anyway, maybe higher. 

Setup:
-------
Overnight boronization required. Standard prescription. 
Post-boronization ECDC in He, as long as we can get but at least two
hours. Might consider not starting the run until 9:00 in order to get more
ECDC, especially if we are planning to go past 18:00 anyway.  

Engineering Setup:
-----------------
Cryopump on for first shot (may decide to turn it off later?)

Gas setup:
     B-top          6psi D2 ENABLED
     B-main        40psi D2 ENABLED
     B-side Lower   2psi Ar DISABLED
     B-side Upper  as is He3 Disabled for Step 0, ENABLE for all 7.8T shots
     H-Bot         40psi D2 DISABLED (may need for additional fueling at
                                      higher currents)
     B-DIV         20psi N2 DISABLED (for seeding, if needed)
     H-DIV         as is    DISABLED

     NINJA C-port  8psi He DISABLED (for GPI)
     NINJA F-port 10psi D2 DISABLED for CXRS &inboard) 
                                    May use for additional inboard fueling at
                                    higher Ip. 
Engineering Power System Setup
-------------------------------

Step 0: As on 1160708001 (5.4T, 800kA) OR alternate suggested by JWH. 
Step 1-N: As on 1160729008 (7.8T), alternator to 1716 rpm
  

Shot Sequence
--------------

0) Boronization recovery: No idea yet what to do for this. The RF is different
enough at 5.4T it's not clear if we save any time doing it there. On the
initial run on this MP on 1160708 we took 10 shots at 5.4T to recover. To
reproduce the same sequence, the starting point 1160708001 would be
appropriate. 
 
It has been suggested that these shots be used for discharge development for
upside-down forward field Super H-mode experiment based on 1150722032. Rather
than attempt to do all the field reversals, flips, and time reversals on this
example, I would suggest starting from an USN forward-field I-mode case and
bringing up the lower xpoint and ZCUR to make it closse to DN (upper) and then
introduce a downward move to transition to LSN. Possible starting point for
this could be 1160617017. 
Allocation for step 0: [5-10 shots @5.4T], 1-2.5 hours. 

0.a) Load from 1160708001 (5.4T, 800kA) or MP830 development shot from Jerry. 
Implement  sweeping strikes up and down the vertical
plate. Run up to 5 shots to get RF steady, reduce RF "fueling". Exercise Argon
valve at the end of at least one shot, then turn off. [1-5 shots]

0.b) Run locked mode shot, e.g. 1160725013 or lm shot from Wednesday morning
[1-2 shots]

0.c) If it appears necessary, run intentional disruption to reduce neutral
pressure, RF "fueling" effect. Move ZCUR sharply down and turn off ZCUR3 gains
at 1.0sec [0-1 shot]

0.d) Continue RF recovery, as needed [0-3 shots]

1) Reload from 1160729008 (7.8T, 1.4MA). Turn off argon puff (we've already
got HIREX data on this one). Attempt to reproduce this shot with as much power
as RF can manage. Adjust B-side Upper (He3) puff based on PCI data (probably
down to 100 or 125msec from 150ms. [2-3 shots], 1-1.5 hours.
  Note: PO should update dpcs_lowpass_obs to apply to wires [10,14] segs
  [2,3,4] and consider raising P,D and reducing PG3 feedforward, at least
  by Step #2.
  
2) Increase Ip from 1.4 to 1.6MA, aiming for q95~3.3 . Increase NL04 target to
1.6e20. Depending on whether Step 1 was better than the reference shot,
consider turning Argon back on. This step is the first new thing for this day.
Adjust RF waveforms, He3 puff (guided by PCI results) to get into EDA,
increase power to max possible during EDA. Consider seeding, changing
strikepoint sweeps, gaps, to reduce Mo influx (if it's a problem).
If RF power is insufficient to get L-H at the higher density, then try going
to step 3 (higher kappa, closer to DN), maybe up to SSEP > -1mm, to take
advantage of the "sweet spot"  at DN. Alternatively, start in the LSN slot,
then sweep onto the vertical plate. 
Step 2: [1-5 shots], 0.5-2.5 hours
 
3) Increase elongation, decrease SSEP. Aim for kappa=1.7, SSEP=-5mm Evaluate
change in q95, cryopumping, neutral pressure, RF coupling, Wmhd. 
Step 3:  [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

4) Increase Ip again, aiming to get back to q95~3.2 or so, with the higher
elongation. Expect this will be about 1.7 or 1.8MA, nl04 target to
1.8e20. 
Step 4: [1-3 shots], 0.5-1.5 hours

5) Depending on the time, and whatever is decided to do next, push toward
2MA, q95<3. Or push it up to DN, if that looks more promising. 

6) If/when we get to a point that further increases in current are not
compatible with EDA, or it gets to be 18:00, 
then move on to one of the alternate Run Plans for high
performance (ELM-free at high current, "Super H-mode" approach, Improvements
to 5.4T, 1.3MA case 1160718013, ...).

Once shot is realized, adjust the timing of the SSEP sweep using the ZCUR program. Rather than ramping ZCUR slowly, program a jog at 0.7s that takes SSEP from about +0.004 to -0.002. 3. Begin increasing RF as quickly as possible, attempting to get ~3MW for ~100ms in the USN phase and make a high Te pedestal, as measured by ECE/TS. Consider raising ICRF power after H-mode transition.

During the progress of MP813, we may wish to periodically revisit the USN-->LSN shot to monitor how it is responding to changing wall conditions. Shots 035--043 were attempts to further exploit the low-density, hot pedestal that is often observed when transitioning to H-mode from a hot L-mode or I-mode. We had a very interesting run at this in reversed field on 1160922, in which the I-H was sought by jogging the plasma from LSN toward USN. The final shot on that run had pedestal parameters suggestive of the super H regime predicted by Snyder, and achieved >220kJ stored energy with only 1MA of current.
We worked to reproduce this scheme in forward field by designing a discharge that sweeps from USN to LSN and drops the outer strike point down into the lower divertor for the H-mode phase. We were allowed to do some discharge development on this early in the run during boronization recovery in the MP813 session (thanks Wolfe and Hutch!) By shot 35 we were ready to make the final tweaks to shaping, density and power programs.
We got 9 shot cycles and 7 successful plasmas with which to make our stab at history.
__ What we learned: __
H-mode transitions occurred pretty reliably when SSEP began decreasing through +2mm or +1mm
Getting into a nice hot I-mode required the magnetic balance to be clearly biased away from DN. Pushing SSEP more positive (to ~+4mm) was needed in order to obtain a good I-mode, that stayed hot and avoided an I-L-H transition on the SSEP jog.
The scheme was applicable at Ip values of 1.0, 1.2 and 1.4MA. (The last Ip point was made possible by raising Bt to 5.7T.
Mo content in the heated L and I-mode phases was high. This may be due to poorer impurity screening in the upper divertor.
The lower divertor did nothing magical to reduce the influx of Mo into the H-mode. We did not see too much in the way of long-lived H-modes seen previously when doing this in reversed field. Attempts to tamp the Mo down by seeding N2 were also limited in what they could do.
We could not reproduce the confinement of shot 1160922032 at 1MA. However after some development we did obtain a 192kJ peak at 1MA, which surpassed (barely) the peak obtained by Reinke at 1MA. Ultimately we obtained 235kJ at 1.4MA (shot 042), but could not improve beyond this with our one remaining shot.
There are possible approaches to the super H-mode channel in some of these cases, to be analyzed in conjunction with the MP830 shots from 1160922.

Still hacking away at the analysis of the nondim imode scans.
I've finally (I think) got a version of build_dataset3.pro that includes
rhoi_star_val based on TI0_HIREX and nu_C_ece_val based on the ECE Te0;
the stdev on the nu_c_ece is still very large because I'm not smoothing
over the sawteeth. Also, I have to manually account for the missing 
Ti0_Hirex on the last two slices (shot#30). The way I have it set up now,
the values of rhoi_star are coming out around 0.0001, because although I 
record !values.f_nan as the ti0_hirex signal for missing value, I use
(ti0_hirex > 0.01) in the rhoi_star expression to avoid taking ln(0), and
this comes out 0.01 instead of NaN. 

Anyhow, if I select those out, I can run the multiple regression as:
IDL> ix = where(data.conf_vals.rhoi_star_val ge .001,nx)
IDL> lrho = alog(data[ix].conf_vals.rhoi_star_val)
IDL> lnu = alog(data[ix].conf_Vals.nu_c_ece_val)
IDL> lbeta = alog(data[ix].conf_vals.betat_val)
IDL> lbtau = alog(data[ix].conf_vals.btaue_val)
IDL> cc = regress(transpose([[lrho],[lnu],[lbeta]]),lbtau,chisq=chi2,const=const,corr=corr,meas=data[ix].conf_vals.btaue_sig/data[ix].conf_vals.btaue_val,sigma=sigma,yfit=yf)
IDL> print,cc
     -2.77658
    -0.286277
     0.365524
IDL> print,sigma
     0.420414     0.150715     0.284251
IDL> print,const
     -16.3621

For what it's worth, this gives alpha_rho=-2.78 +/ 0.42
alpha_nu = -0.29 +/- 0.15
alpha_beta = 0.38 +/- 0.28

with a chisq=17.5 for (14-4)=10 dof, close but not great.

I should look at this more carefully, but it now seems reasonably close to 
gyroBohm with some weak but maybe significant nu and beta dependence. 
Better than it was! Doing some sawtooth averaging on the nu_c may help a 
little, although the abscissa error bars don't come in to the fitting sigma.

What I really need to look at is the individual scans, with nearly fixed
secondary values. That was the point of the experiment, after all.

Ted and I, with the help of Alan and Willie, replaced a defective rectifier in our RF power supply, which seemed to help a bit, for a while, until the unit died again. Looks like the system gave up the ghost today. RIP PCI.

SL_SUMMARY for first part of Friday, Sep 30, 2016
MP#813
SL: wolfe
PO: Hutch, Marmar
EO: Cochran, Pfeiffer, Byford, Toland, Pierson

Definitely a glass half-full run. We did raise Ip to 1.8MA, and got H-modes, 
and we increased kapppa~1.7, and SSEP to -3mm or so at the highest current.
Maximum stored energy reached ~240kJ. 
Unfortunately, we had no EDA H-modes for currents higher than 1.4MA, which we 
had previously obtained on 1160729008. 

Good shots were

Shots      Ip     q95   kappa  Wmhd    Mode
-----      ---    ---   -----  -----   ----
 14        1.4    3.8    1.59   208    EDA
 20        1.5    3.85   1.68   198    Elm-free
 21        1.7    3.4    1.69   239    Elm-free
 22        1.8    3.3    1.69   245    Elm-free

We had a long (3 hour) delay in the morning trying to recover from the
effects of a power glitch last night, mostly on the data system. It also
turned out that the PCI was also put out of action by the glitch, which 
meant we couldn't track the MC to optimize the He3 puff. First plasma 
shot was #4, at 11:35AM; so much for an 8:00AM start. Boronization recovery
at 5.4T lasted until shot#12. 

There were problems keeping the RF on at over 4MW, and we had a number of
shots that lasted full length in L-mode. All of the later H-mode shots
had RF faults that took a while to recover at some point in the flattop.

A disruption on the last shot, #23, was due to the Ip gain switch coming up
with too large an error after we attempted to ramp the current up faster. 
Probably could have dealt with that, but the RF was continuing to fault,
so we turned over to the next experiment at 18:30.
